        "# Overview of PIE grammar\n",
        "\n",
        "## Word order in English\n",
        "\n",
        "-   The boy hugged the tree.\n",
        "-   The tree hugged the boy.\n",
        "\n",
        "> Indicates the role of a nominal in a sentence\n",
        "\n",
        "## Subject vs Object\n",
        "\n",
        "<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "### The boy hugged the tree.\n",
        "\n",
        "-   'The boy' is the subject of the sentence.\n",
        "-   'The tree' is the object of the sentence.\n",
        "\n",
        "> The **subject** of a sentence tells us who or what is *verbing*.\\\n",
        "> The **direct object** of a sentence tells us who or what is *verbed*.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Word order in English\n",
        "\n",
        "<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "### The tree hugged the boy.\n",
        "\n",
        "> What is the subject? What is the direct object?\n",
        "\n",
        "## Languages with Case Systems\n",
        "\n",
        "-   Latin:\n",
        "    -   *Agricola poetam videt.* ‘The farmer sees the poet’\n",
        "    -   *Agricolam poeta videt.* ‘The poet sees the farmer’\n",
        "    -   *Poeta agricolam videt.* ‘The poet sees the farmer’\n",
        "    -   *Poetam agricola videt.* ‘The farmer sees the poet’\n",
        "\n",
        "> Word order is more flexible because the words themselves contain the information about the roles in the sentence.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Discuss with a partner:\n",
        "\n",
        "-   Latin:\n",
        "    -   *Agricola poetam videt.* ‘The farmer sees the poet’\n",
        "    -   *Agricolam poeta videt.* ‘The poet sees the farmer’\n",
        "    -   *Poeta agricolam videt.* ‘The poet sees the farmer’\n",
        "    -   *Poetam agricola videt.* ‘The farmer sees the poet’\n",
        "\n",
        "> In the sentences above, which ending indicates the **nominative case** (the subject) and which one is the **accusative case** (the direct object)?\n",
        "\n",
        "## English often uses:\n",
        "\n",
        "-   **prepositions**:\n",
        "    -   The boy is **in** the tree.\n",
        "    -   The boy is **next to** the tree.\n",
        "    -   The boy runs away **from** the tree.\n",
        "    -   The boy runs **to** the tree.\n",
        "    -   The boy carves **into** the tree **with** a knife.\n",
        "    -   The boy plucks apples **from** the tree **for** his mom.\n",
        "\n",
        "> locations of nominals in space and time, or how they relate to other words in the sentence\n",
        "\n",
        "## For nominals, PIE often uses:\n",
        "\n",
        "-   **endings**\n",
        "\n",
        "    -   nominals: case/number/gender\n",
        "\n",
        "> What do we mean by number? Gender?\n",
        "\n",
        "## Nominals\n",
        "\n",
        "-   Nouns\n",
        "-   Adjectives\n",
        "-   Pronouns\n",
        "\n",
        "## Nominals\n",
        "\n",
        "-   **Case** (what role?)\n",
        "-   **Number** (sg/du/pl)\n",
        "-   **Gender** (m/f/n)\n",
        "-   **Stem class** (o-stem, ah₂-stem, root noun, etc.) \\<-- more on this later!\n",
        "\n",
        "## Nominals\n",
        "\n",
        "-   **Case** (what role?)\n",
        "-   **Number** (sg/du/pl)\n",
        "-   **Gender** (m/f/n)\n",
        "-   **Stem class** (o-stem, ah₂-stem, root noun, etc.)\n",
        "\n",
        "> **When translating:**\\\n",
        "> Find the ending → identify case/number/gender → identify word's function in the sentence.\n",
        "\n",
        "## PIE Cases\n",
        "\n",
        "-   **Nominative**: subject (“the wolf”)\n",
        "-   **Vocative**: address (“yo wolf!”)\n",
        "-   **Accusative**: direct object / motion-goal (“see the wolf”)\n",
        "-   **Instrumental**: means (“with a wolf”)\n",
        "-   **Dative**: recipient / “to/for the wolf”\n",
        "-   **Ablative**: source (“from the wolf”)\n",
        "-   **Genitive**: possession / “of” (“tail of the wolf”)\n",
        "-   **Locative**: location (“in/on/at the wolf”)\n",
        "\n",
        "## PIE Cases\n",
        "\n",
        "| **Case**         | **PIE form** | **Function / Meaning**  |\n",
        "|------------------|--------------|-------------------------|\n",
        "| **Nominative**   | **wĺ̥kʷos**   | “the wolf” (subject)    |\n",
        "| **Vocative**     | **wĺ̥kʷe**    | “yo, wolf!” (address)   |\n",
        "| **Accusative**   | **wĺ̥kʷom**   | \"the wolf” (object)     |\n",
        "| **Instrumental** | **wĺ̥kʷoh**   | “with a wolf”           |\n",
        "| **Dative**       | **wĺ̥kʷōy**   | “to / for the wolf”     |\n",
        "| **Ablative**     | **wĺ̥kʷōd**   | “from the wolf”         |\n",
        "| **Genitive**     | **wĺ̥kʷosyo** | “of the wolf”           |\n",
        "| **Locative**     | **wĺ̥kʷoi**   | “in / on / at the wolf” |\n",
        "\n",
        "## English verbs also use:\n",
        "\n",
        "-   endings\n",
        "    -   The boy hug*s* the tree.\n",
        "    -   The boy hug*ged* the tree.\n",
        "-   helper words\n",
        "    -   The boy *could* hug the tree.\n",
        "    -   The boy *will* hug the tree.\n",
        "-   helper words and endings\n",
        "    -   The boy *is* hug*ging* the tree.\n",
        "    -   The boy *has* hug*ged* the tree.\n",
        "\n",
        "## PIE verbs often use:\n",
        "\n",
        "-   **endings**\n",
        "\n",
        "    -   person/number/tense/aspect/mood\n",
        "\n",
        "-   stem alternations (**ablaut**)\n",
        "\n",
        "-   derivational morphology (**suffixes**)\n",
        "\n",
        "## The basic units\n",
        "\n",
        "-   **Root**: core meaning (e.g. *\\*bʰer-* ‘to carry’)\n",
        "-   **Stem**: root + suffix + ablaut grade (e.g. *\\*bʰére-* ‘carry’, present stem)\n",
        "-   **Ending**: tells you the grammatical job (e.g. *\\*-ti*, 3rd singular)\n",
        "\n",
        "## The basic units\n",
        "\n",
        "Put it together:\n",
        "\n",
        "> **bʰéreti** 'he/she/it carries'\n",
        "\n",
        "## The basic units\n",
        "\n",
        "You can change the ending:\n",
        "\n",
        "> **bʰéresi** 'you carry'\n",
        "\n",
        "## The basic units\n",
        "\n",
        "You can change the stem:\n",
        "\n",
        "> **bʰoréyeti** '(s)he makes (someone) carry'\n",
        "\n",
        "## The basic units\n",
        "\n",
        "Or the root:\n",
        "\n",
        "> **léĝeti** '(s)he gathers'\n",
        "\n",
        "## Verbs: what you track\n",
        "\n",
        "-   **Person/number**: 1/2/3; sg/du/pl\n",
        "-   **Tense/aspect**: present, aorist, perfect\n",
        "-   **Mood**: indicative, imperative, optative, subjunctive\n",
        "-   **Voice**: active, mediopassive\n",
        "\n",
        "## Verbs: what you track\n",
        "\n",
        "-   **Person/number**\n",
        "-   **Tense/aspect**\n",
        "-   **Mood**\n",
        "-   **Voice**\n",
        "\n",
        "**When translating:**\\\n",
        "Figure out *who's* doing the action from the verb's ending first. From there, figure out the tense, etc.\n",
        "\n",
        "## PIE Word Order\n",
        "\n",
        "-   Often characterize as **SOV (subject + object + verb)**, but it’s very flexible.\n",
        "    -   Endings carry a lot of the load, so word order can be freer.\n",
